SATIRE V.

In this Satire, which has a good deal of humour in it, Horace takes up the practice of will-hunting, of which, as of many other degrading vices that afterwards pervaded Roman society, he saw only the beginning. . Describing the rage for making money in Epp. i. 1. 77, he says,— ·

“ Pars hominum gestit conducere publica: sunt qui

Crustis et pomis viduas venentur avaras Excipiantque senes quos in vivaria mittant.'’
